titleproper.value: Guide to the Harris Pierce Photographs<lb/>1888-1900<lb/> <num>PR 270</num>

author.value: Collection processed by Lucas Buresch and Kelly McAnnaney

creation.value: This finding aid was produced using ArchivesSpace <date>2019-05-14T03:23:00</date>

abstract.value: Photographs of street gradings and improvements, as well as residences and businesses in the Bronx during the mid 1890s. Digital copies of the images in the collection are available on-line through the <extref actuate="onRequest" href="http://digitalcollections.nyhistory.org/islandora/object/nyhs%3Apierce">Digital Collections</extref> pages of N-YHS's website.

p.value: Open to qualified researchers, by advance appointment only. To schedule an appointment, contact the Print Room Librarian at printroom@nyhistory.org.
This collection should be cited as: Harris Pierce photographs, PR 270, Department of Prints, Photographs, and Architectural Collections, New-York Historical Society.

The photographs appear to have been made as evidence in supporting the cases of claimants filing for damages against the city. Some of the photographs are mounted on boards with a form on the verso for recording information about the image. The form includes the names of Thomas S. Bassford and Ernest Hall, lawyers representing the claimants.
The only photograph in the collection that is known not to have been made by Harris Pierce is the view of 1940 Park Avenue taken by Louis C. Bennett.
